ASIAN ECONOMIC NEWS via NewsNet
January 1, 1996

Philippines to cut tariffs on 155 products in '96+

MANILA, Dec. 26 Kyodo

     The Philippines will lower import tariffs on some 155 products
next year as part of an accelerated program to create a free trade
market in Southeast Asia by 2003, Association of Southeast Asian
Nations (ASEAN) documents said Tuesday.
     According to the documents, the 155 items are among 717 products
in Manila's temporary exclusion list to be included in the Common
Effective Preferential Tariff (CEPT) scheme over the next five years.
     The CEPT is the vehicle for creating a free trade area within
the ASEAN region, home of the world's fastest growing economies.
     ASEAN groups Brunei, Indonesia, Malaysia, the Philippines,
Singapore, Thailand and Vietnam.
     Throughout ASEAN, about 687 tariff lines will be lowered in
1996 and 2,496 others in the next four years.  Average tariff rates
will subsequently be brought down from 7.73% in 1996 to 4.03% by
2000 and 2.90% by 2003.
     ASEAN member economies vowed at the end of the fifth leaders'
summit in Bangkok on Dec. 15 to speed up the realization of an ASEAN
Free Trade Area even before the target date year of 2003 by
maximizing the number of items whose tariffs can be reduced to 0-5%
by the year 2000, as well as expanding the number of products whose
tariffs can be reduced to zero percent by the same year.



