January 1, 1996

2 Toyota affiliates set up joint ventures in China+

NAGOYA, Dec. 26 Kyodo

     Two major affiliates of Toyota Motor Corp. announced Tuesday
the establishment of joint ventures with the affiliates of a major
Chinese carmaker to manufacture auto parts in Tianjin, southeast of
Beijing.
     The Chinese carmaker is Tianjin Automotive Industrial (Group)
Co., with which Toyota Motor is now negotiating to set up a joint
venture to produce passenger cars.
     Nippondenso Co., a major maker of electronic car parts, said it
has set up Tianjin Denso Engine Electrical Products Co., in
conjunction with Tianjin Internal Combustion Engine Generator and
Starter Factory.
     The joint venture, capitalized at 1.66 billion yen, will be
owned 55% by Tianjin Internal Combustion and the remainder by
Nippondenso and the Toyota group's trading house, Toyota Tsusho
Corp., the company said.
     The new joint venture will produce starters and alternators for
use in automobiles to be made by Tianjin Automotive Industrial, it
said.
     In a related development, Toyoda Gosei Co. established Tianjin
Toyoda Gosei Automobile Hose Co. in conjunction with a Chinese
business partner that also belongs to the group of companies led by
Tianjin Automotive Industrial, the company said.
     The joint venture, capitalized at 384 million yen, is owned
64.4% by Toyoda Gosei, 5% by Toyota Tsusho and the remainder by the
Chinese partner.
     The joint venture will produce brake hoses for use in
automobiles to be built by Tianjin Automotive Industrial.
     If the Chinese government approves a Toyota application to set
up a joint venture with Tianjing Automotive Industrial, the two
Toyota affiliates want to supply parts to be made by their new joint
ventures to Toyota's own joint venture with Tianjin Automotive too,
the pair said.
     Toyota is offering to produce passenger car engines with Tianjin
Automotive Industrial in view of the possible Chinese partner's plan
to introduce a new car model, Toyota officials said.



