January 1, 1996

IHI gets order to build 3 blast furnaces in Taiwan+

TOKYO, Dec. 28 Kyodo

     Ishikawajima-Harima Heavy Industries Co. (IHI) announced
Thursday it has signed a deal with a major Taiwanese steelmaker to
construct three blast furnaces in Taiwan for about 40 billion yen.
     The steelmaker, Taiwan Steel Co., plans to build the furnaces at
a new plant near the city of Tainan, southwestern Taiwan, which will
start up in the year 2000 with an annual steel production capacity of
7.5 million tons, the Japanese comprehensive heavy machinery maker
said.
     The construction of the first blast furnace will be completed by
the end of 1999, and the Taiwanese firm plans to start operations in
June 2000, IHI said.
     The other furnaces will begin working by June 2002, IHI said.
     Each of the three furnaces has an internal volume of 3,800 cubic
meters, it said.
     With the new plant, Taiwan Steel intends to increase its share
of the domestic market where imports, mostly from Japan and South
Korea, currently account for about half the market, an IHI official
said.



