Sumitomo to take stake in Indonesian chemical maker+

TOKYO, Dec. 28 Kyodo

     Sumitomo Corp. said Thursday it will purchase 25 million
dollars worth of convertible bonds to be issued in January by an
Indonesian chemical maker belonging to the Salim group, the largest
financial group in Indonesia.
     The Japanese general trading house will convert the bonds into
stocks after the redemption term matures in four years, meaning it
will take some stake in the equity of the chemical maker, PT Sulfindo
Ajiusaha, a Sumitomo official said.
     Sumitomo will also buy the chemical maker's debentures of the
same amount in January, the official said.
     The Indonesian maker plans to issue in January 100 million
dollars worth of bonds, half of which are convertible bonds, in order
to double its chlorine production for polyvinyl chloride resin, he
said.
     The remaining half of the bonds will be purchased by the Salim
group, he said.
     Sumitomo and the Salim group earlier set up two joint ventures
in Indonesia to produce polyvinyl chloride resin, and chlorine to be
made at the facilities will be used in the resin production, the
official said.



