January 1, 1996

Hyundai group picks Chung's son as new chairman+

SEOUL, Dec. 28 Kyodo

     South Korea's Hyundai business group named Chung Mong Koo, the
second-eldest son of its honorary chairman and founder Chung Ju
Yung, as its new chairman on Thursday.
     In the largest shake-up since its founding, Hyundai replaced 404
top-level managers of its affiliated companies.
     Chung Mong Koo, 58, was chairman of Hyundai Precision and Ind.
Co.
     Chung Se Yung, the 67-year-old group chairman and younger
brother of group founder Chung Ju Yung, was named as honorary
chairman of Hyundai Motor Service Co.
     Chung Mong Kyu, Chung Se Yung's 32-year-old son and vice
president of Hyundai Motor Service Co., was elevated to the No.1
position of the automaker as new chairman.
     A Hyundai group spokesman said in a statement, ''the average age
of top management directors was greatly lowered with the reshuffle,
bringing in new wind and vitality into overall group management.''
     Chung Mong Hun, 47, the fifth-eldest son of the group founder
and chairman of Hyundai Electronics Co., was named as vice chairman
of the Hyundai group to support his elder brother.
     Four top-level managers of Hyundai-affiliated companies,
including the chairman of Hyundai Corp., Lee Choon Lim, were
transferred to advisory posts, removing them from the first line of
the group management.



