<HR>
<A NAME = "32"></A>Copyright
ASIAN ECONOMIC NEWS via NewsNet
January 1, 1996

Japan moves on economic sea zone could spark rows: paper+

TOKYO, Dec. 29 Kyodo

     The government is moving toward ratifying the international
ocean treaty and creating a 200-mile exclusive economic zone that
will likely inflame territorial disputes with China and South Korea,
the Tokyo Shimbun reported Friday.
     The daily said in a front-page article that the government hopes
to ratify the 1982 U.N. Convention on the Law of the Sea during the
upcoming regular Diet session and establish the exclusive economic
zone.
     The convention, which went into force in November last year,
obliges all signatories to recognize an exclusive 200-mile economic
zone off a nation's coasts.
     Within their zones, states have the exclusive right to fish or
to exploit natural resources such as oil, reclaim land or construct
artificial islands.
     In question will be Japan's dispute with China over the Senkaku
Islands, known in Chinese as the Diaoyutai Islands, in the East China
Sea.
     Tokyo also disputes South Korea's claim to Takeshima Island,
known as Tokto in Korea, in the Sea of Japan.
     The Senkaku Islands, located some 150 kilometers northeast of
the northern tip of Taiwan, are also claimed by Taipei.
     China has said it plans to ratify the sea convention next
summer.  South Korea has already ratified the treaty.
     Some Foreign Ministry officials said earlier this month Japan
should delineate a 200-mile zone with the Senkaku Islands as a
base of reference, arguing that refraining from doing so could be
interpreted by the Chinese as a lack of interest in the territory.



<A HREF ="#HeadList">Back to Headline List</A><BR>
<HR>
<A NAME = "33"></A>Copyright
ASIAN ECONOMIC NEWS via NewsNet
January 1, 1996

Japanese help Indonesian village improve iron casting+

URAWA, Japan, Dec. 29 Kyodo

     The Japanese city of Kawaguchi in Saitama Prefecture, bordering
Tokyo, famous for its cast-iron pots and pans, is helping an
Indonesian village bring its metal-casting technology up to date by
introducing modern cupola furnaces.
     Six makers of cast-iron products in Kawaguchi have founded the
Kasia metal-casting technology exchange cooperative hoping to help
realize a model factory in Ceper, a village on Java, by the middle of
next year, said Kenichi Masuda, head of the cooperative.
     Because of the strong yen, the Kawaguchi makers have suffered
from sluggish demand, even for products made from new materials such
as ceramics.  They have embarked on the project in a bid to overcome
the mood of the recession, he said.
     The name ''Kasia'' is a contraction of Kawaguchi and Asia.
Ceper has some 300 metal casters who make their products in
hand-shaped sand molds.
     ''Their technological level equals that of Japan in the Edo
period (1615-1868), with rejects sometimes amounting to almost 80%
of production,'' Masuda said.
     The idea for the project was born when the head of a
metal-casting cooperative from Ceper requested technological
assistance after inspecting Masuda's factory during a visit to Japan
in 1991.
     The village is providing the site and the factory free of
charge.  Kawaguchi workers skilled in the latest metal-casting
techniques will serve as instructors at the Ceber model factory and
bring the know-how of some 20 local metalworkers up to date.
     Also planned are a library and a metal-casting contest.
     Indonesia relies heavily on imports for cast-iron products,
particularly machine parts.
     Japanese makers producing in Indonesia are not able to keep up
with demand.  Masuda, though, said he does not expect the model
factory to make profits right from the start.
     ''We are ready to live with a deficit in the first few years.
For us, the project is significant in giving new impetus to Japan's
metal-casting industry which is in a fix.''



<A HREF ="#HeadList">Back to Headline List</A><BR>
<HR>
<A NAME = "34"></A>Copyright
ASIAN ECONOMIC NEWS via NewsNet
January 1, 1996

Steelmakers face price-cut pressure for exports to Asia+

TOKYO, Dec. 29 Kyodo

     Japanese steelmakers are under growing pressure to cut prices
of Asia-bound steel products due to a glut in the market, steel
companies officials said Friday.
     They said China's restraint on economic expansion, including a
switch to a tight credit policy, is primarily responsible for the
glut.
     The Chinese government has ordered domestic steelmakers to limit
their production to reduce large inventories resulting from
overproduction in 1994, they said.
     China's crude steel output was estimated at 90 million tons in
1994.
     Japanese steel producers recently bowed to a Chinese demand for
a price cut of about 8.0% for their steel shipments in the
February-July period.
     The officials said Japanese steel companies already face growing
calls for price cuts from Thailand, Singapore and Malaysia.
     Prices of steel products bound for India and the Middle East
have also declined by about 10% from the July-September level of
this year.
     Trading houses said some Japanese steelmakers have offered
price cuts of up to 15% to secure export volume.



<A HREF ="#HeadList">Back to Headline List</A><BR>
<HR>
<A NAME = "35"></A>Copyright
ASIAN ECONOMIC NEWS via NewsNet
January 1, 1996

Thailand's population to reach 60 mil. next June+

BANGKOK, Dec. 29 Kyodo

     Thailand' population will reach 60 million by June 1996 and
will rise to 70.48 million by 2012, Mahidol University's Institute
for Population and Social Research said Friday.
     Thailand will have 59.71 million -- 29.84 million males and
29.87 million females -- as of Jan. 1, 1996, according to the
quarterly Mahidol Population Gazette released by the institute.
     It said the urban and rural populations are now 18.86 million
and 40.85 million respectively.  Bangkok has 7.85 million people.
     The gazette said life expectancy at birth is 66.6 years for men
and 71.7 years for women.



<A HREF ="#HeadList">Back to Headline List</A><BR>
<HR>
<A NAME = "36"></A>Copyright
ASIAN ECONOMIC NEWS via NewsNet
January 1, 1996

China to cut tariffs, spell out new rules+

BEIJING, Dec 29 Kyodo

     China will cut import tariffs on 4,000 items by an average 35%
beginning April 1, 1996, while preferential policies for foreign
investment projects already approved will enjoy a transition period,
state press reported Friday.
     In a bid to level the playing field among China's backward
inland regions and its booming special economic zones, and to offer
foreign enterprises the same treatment as domestic one, the State
Council has issued a circular calling for the reduction of the
general tariff rate to 23%.
     It also called for an end to the duty-free benefits enjoyed by
the special economic zones, the Economic Daily said.
     The circular conforms with the tariff cuts promised by Chinese
President Jiang Zemin at the Osaka informal summit meeting of
Asia-Pacific Economic Cooperation (APEC) forum in October and is seen
as a significant step toward China's entry into the World Trade
Organization.
     No information was provided on the precise size of reductions or
which products would have their import duties cut.
     However, regulations were set out regarding a transition period
for preferential tax policies and duty-free benefits for foreign
investment projects legally approved before the publication of the
circular.
     Foreign investment projects worth more than 30 million dollars
and approved before Dec. 28 would continue to enjoy their reduced and
duty-free tariffs and preferential import taxes on imported equipment
and raw materials until Dec. 31, 1997, it said, while such projects
valued under 30 million dollars could extend the previous policy
until Dec. 31, 1996.
     Equipment for technological transformation approved for import
before the issuance of the circular would also continue to enjoy
previous preferential import policies during the transition period,
it said.
     If equipment and resources are not imported within the specified
transition periods, enterprises could ask the Ministry of Foreign
Trade and Economic Cooperation or the State Economic and Trade
Commission for an extension from the State Council, it said.



<A HREF ="#HeadList">Back to Headline List</A><BR>
<HR>
<A NAME = "37"></A>Copyright
ASIAN ECONOMIC NEWS via NewsNet
January 1, 1996

China breaks another grain output record in '95+

BEIJING, Dec. 29 Kyodo

     Chinese farmers harvested a record 466 million tons of grain in
1995, up 21 million tons over last year and nearly 10 million tons
over the previous record harvest in 1993, Xinhua News Agency
reported Friday.
     The record output came, though several grain growing areas were
plagued by natural disaster during the year and rising costs for
fertilizer and pesticides threatened to keep farmers off the land.
     ''With the rise in grain prices mainly blamed for last year's
high inflation rate, the 1995 increase in output is a great help in
the nation's efforts at curbing inflation and easing the strained
grain market,'' analysts said, according to Xinhua.
     Government officials have set a grain production target of 500
million tons for the year 2000, as China's rising living standard is
expected to increase grain consumption, especially of feed grains.
     According to the Hong Kong-based China Agribusiness Review 1995,
following trends in the first half of the year, China is expected to
become a net grain importer this year after being a significant
exporter over the last two years.



<A HREF ="#HeadList">Back to Headline List</A><BR>
<HR>
<A NAME = "38"></A>Copyright
ASIAN ECONOMIC NEWS via NewsNet
January 1, 1996

Ramos signs 394.8 bil. peso budget for '96+

MANILA, Dec. 29 Kyodo

     President Fidel Ramos signed into law Friday a 394.8 billion
peso (about 15 billion U.S. dollar) budget for 1996, with education
getting the biggest chunk of the funds, presidential palace and
Congress officials announced.
     The budget also earmarked large outlays to public works,
defense and assistance to local governments, House Speaker Jose de
Venecia said.
     It also reflects a doubled budget for agriculture to help the
sector cope with the immediate effects of tariff and subsidy cuts
under the General Agreement on Tariffs and Trade, and includes a 4
billion peso (about 15 million dollar) fund for poverty alleviation,
de Venecia said.
     The budget department said that while general appropriations
come to 394.8 billion pesos, the total obligatory budget approved by
Congress was 415.6 billion pesos (about 16 billion dollars),
including 25.3 billion pesos (97 million dollars) for automatic debt
service payments.
     Congress initially wanted to include debt-service funds in the
general appropriations, but Ramos vetoed the move, noting that the
Supreme Court has already ruled that funds for debt servicing are
automatically appropriated and need not be included in the yearly
budget.



<A HREF ="#HeadList">Back to Headline List</A><BR>
<HR>
<A NAME = "39"></A>Copyright
ASIAN ECONOMIC NEWS via NewsNet
January 1, 1996

Remitted funds from Asian contract workers top ODA+

MANILA, Dec. 29 Kyodo

     The aggregate sum of remittances to home countries from
overseas contract workers from nine Asian countries has shot up to
dwarf the annual total of official development assistance (ODA) to
the nine, an Asian Development Bank investigation shows.
     Remittances from such workers to the nine countries totaled 75
billion dollars in 1993, exceeding their aggregate ODA of 54 billion
dollars from industrialized countries, including Japan, the survey
shows.
     The survey covered the Philippines, Thailand, India, Bangladesh,
Indonesia, Sri Lanka, Pakistan, China and South Korea.
     In the Philippines and Indonesia, the ratio of contract workers'
annual remittances to the nations' gross domestic product (GDP) is on
the rise, according to figures collated by the Manila-based regional
lending institution.
     In a period from 1987 to 1993, the aggregate of remittances home
from Indonesian contract workers abroad quadrupled from 86 million
dollars to 346 million dollars, while that of Filipino workers showed
a 2.4-fold jump from 1.02 billion dollars to 2.54 million dollars,
the survey showed.
     In contrast, the aggregate home remittances from Thai and South
Korean workers saw much slower growth ratios over similar periods.
     Aggregate remittances from South Korean workers increased
nearly 50% from 418 million dollars to 605 million dollars from 1987
to 1993, while those from Thai workers grew 40% from 784 million
dollars to 1.13 billion dollars in a period from 1987 to 1992,
according to the bank figures.
     This could imply that a nation's dependence on such remittance
eases as its economy prospers, alleviating the need for contract
workers to go abroad and send money home, analysts said.



