January 1, 1996

MACAU: STUDY IS FINISHED TO INTEGRATE MACAU'S NEW AIRPORT

Feasibility studies have already been completed to build direct road
and high-speed rail connections costing about $1bn to Guangzhou and
Zhuhai from Macau's airport, officially opened by Portugal's president
Mario Soares at the beginning of December.

Talks are also taking place to develop an integrated transit system to
simplify customs and immigration procedures for passengers and cargo
moving between Macau, China and Hong Kong. Macau Airport company
chairman, Dr Antonio Diogo Pinto, said current plans include a $35m
high-speed ferry pier and a massive expansion of air cargo,
warehousing, office and hotel facilities at the airport.

Dr Pinto said the airport, which has only been operating since early
November, has already exceeded expectations. Twelve airlines were
making regular flights by the end of 1995, compared to the 10 that was
forecast. The Macau government has signed air services agreements with
more than 20 countries including Malaysia, Thailand, China and the US.



