January 1, 1996

MASSIVE RECLAMATION IS PROPOSED FOR MACAU

Macau, Portugal's sleepy enclave on China's Pearl River estuary, will
physically grow by one quarter, if a massive $3bn reclamation project
gets the green light. The scheme, the biggest project in Macau's 500-
year existence, has been proposed by Dr Stanley Ho, a Hong Kong casino
and property magnate.

Dr Ho said the scheme will be jointly developed by his company,
Sociedade de Turismo e Diversoes de Macau and Chyau Fwu Development
Company, a Hong Kong property outfit headed by tycoon George Wong. Dr
Ho also owns Shun Tak, a property company which developed much of
Macau.

Central to Dr Ho's development is the China Macau World Trade Centre
complex of 10 hotels, a 660,000 sq m International Trade Mart and a
multi-theme park covering 700,000 sq m. The development will cover
700ha, formed by infilling the sea between Taipa and Coloane islands,
creating a new 'super-island' dubbed Cotai City by property analysts.
The initial phases of the project are due for completion in 1999 to
coincide with Macau's return to Chinese control.

Blueprints have been lodged with the Sino-Portuguese Land Group and the
Macau government's public works department and their decision is
expected in the next few months.



<A HREF ="#HeadList">Back to Headline List</A><BR>
<HR>
<A NAME = "10"></A>Copyright
ASIAN INFRASTRUCTURE MONTHLY via NewsNet
January 1, 1996

HONG KONG: IATA PRONOUNCES HK'S NEW AIRPORT A DISASTER

Hong Kong's new $7.7bn airport has been described as a disaster by
Pierre Jeanniot, the director general of the International Air
Transport Association (IATA). At a recent meeting with the Hong Kong
Airport Authority he said it was a 'waste of time' to open the new
airport without a second runway.

The first runway of the new international airport at Chek Lap Kok is
not expected to open for business until 1998. 'We don't see the point
in spending vast sums of money to build an airport which doesn't
increase capacity,' he said, adding that, if anything, the new airport
would constrain capacity while requiring airlines to pay higher landing
fees - landing and parking fees at Kai Tak, already stretched to
capacity, have increased 28 per cent over the last three years making
it one of the most expensive in the world. IATA's views on the second
runway are shared by Hong Kong's main carrier, Cathay Pacific.

Gordon Sui, secretary for economic services, denied the IATA claim.
'The new airport will operate 24 hours a day, seven days a week, unlike
Kai Tak which is severely restricted by a curfew,' he said recently.
'Even with one runway, existing capacity at the new airport will be
increased from 26 million passengers to 36 million passengers per
year.' Sui also said there had never been any suggestion to build one
runway at Chek Lap Kok. 'The new airport was designed for two runways
and that is exactly what the new airport will have. The opening of a
second runway will be a matter of timing.' He said the government will
be looking at the traffic flow at the new airport before making a final
decision.

Jeanniot said he thought there may be another reason for the
government's reluctance to open the airport with two runways. 'There
seems to be a paralysis in the decision-making process. A feeling that
it is more political than anything else.' The airport project, the
largest single engineering project in the world, has been at the centre
of a fierce political debate between China and Britain since it was
announced in 1989 by the former governor, Sir David Wilson.

That debate has cooled down somewhat and in early December Britain and
China agreed to drop the 'provisional' from the Provisional Airport
Authority. It was seen as a major turning point in the massive project.
Not only is Hong Kong getting a new airport it is also getting the
infrastructure investment that goes with it - a new bridge linking
Kowloon to Lantau Island, massive reclamation to support a highway, and
a rail link to Hong Kong and Kowloon with property developments
springing up around the new stations.

From December 1, 1995 the Airport Authority took over from the
Provisional Airport Authority with pro-China businessman, Wong Po-yan,
at the helm. Recently it went to the market for a massive HK$8.2bn
($1.06bn) syndicated loan and revolving credit. The loan consists of a
HK$6.4bn ($872m) loan and a HK$1.8bn ($233m) revolving facility. The
authority will pay an interest rate of 43 basis points (0.43 percentage
point) above the Hong Kong Interbank Offered Rate for both tranches of
the loan. The Airport Authority was permitted to borrow an additional
HK$3.4bn ($440m) under Sino-British agreements.

In January the Monetary Authority signed an agreement to act as
arranging agent for the Mass Transit Railway Corporation (MTRC) for a
HK$10bn ($1.3bn) note-issuance facility. The Airport Authority has said
it would find such a facility attractive if it carried access to the
Monetary Authority's liquidity adjustment facility. The Airport
Authority's issues would be of shorter maturities than the MTRC issues
because it has to pay off the first part of the project by the end of
2001.

Standard Chartered Bank recently described Hong Kong's existing
international airport as 'an indispensable piece of infrastructure
promoting the territory's rapid economic growth.' But Kai Tak has
reached its full capacity. Between now and the opening day of the new
airport, Kai Tak will become more and more congested. 'An efficient
airport is part and parcel of Hong Kong's competitive advantage in
serving as a business centre for the Asia-Pacific region as well as for
China,' the bank said. It has been estimated that any further delays on
the new airport could cost Hong Kong dearly. Failure to meet projected
rising demand for air transport could cost the territory HK$420bn
($54bn) between 1997 and 2010 the bank said.

More than 20 per cent of aircraft movements at Kai Tak either originate
in China or are destined for the mainland. Kai Tak has proved a
lucrative investment for the Hong Kong government, paying after-tax
returns on average net fixed assets in 1991 of 29 percent.



<A HREF ="#HeadList">Back to Headline List</A><BR>
<HR>
<A NAME = "11"></A>Copyright
ASIAN INFRASTRUCTURE MONTHLY via NewsNet
January 1, 1996

HONG KONG: CONTRACTORS FACE PROBLEMS MEETING CLK'S DEADLINES

Construction of the $1.3bn terminal building at Hong Kong's new airport
at Chek Lap Kok is running more than four months behind schedule even
though the job has been going for just 11 months. The Airport Authority
(AA) said the problems stemmed from earlier delays on the foundations
which were five months late and difficulties faced by the terminal
contractor, BCJ joint venture, mobilising sufficient staff and
equipment. AA corporate development director, Clinton Leeks, said the
Authority is confident the lost time can be clawed back and the airport
'remains on target for substantial completion by mid-1997.' The airport
is due to open in April 1998.

A revised construction schedule has been agreed with BCJ, a consortium
formed by Balfour Beatty and Amec of Britain, Maeda of Japan, Kumagai
Gumi (Hong Kong) and China State Construction Engineering Corporation,
to get the project back on track.

A construction director, Alistair Thomson, said there has also been
mobilisation and ground water problems on the $86m airfield tunnels
contract being undertaken by the UK's Alfred McAlpine, Downer of New
Zealand and Paul Y of Hong Kong. Work was held up for several weeks,
although the contract is back on schedule.

Industry insiders say the difficulties stem from the fast-track nature
of the airport project. 'The AA wants contractors to start as soon as
the contract is agreed on day one. Its just not possible. It takes time
to get staff to Hong Kong and organise the massive amounts of equipment
needed,' commented one construction chief. 'There is also a limit to
how much construction can physically be done. The contract periods are
unrealistic. The foundations are a case in point. Heavy rains probably
held the job up by two months, but the remaining three month delay was
largely caused because the contractor couldn't go any faster,' he
added.



<A HREF ="#HeadList">Back to Headline List</A><BR>
<HR>
<A NAME = "12"></A>Copyright
ASIAN INFRASTRUCTURE MONTHLY via NewsNet
January 1, 1996

HONG KONG: OPPORTUNITIES ARISE FROM CLK'S PRIVATE FACILITIES

Construction of the privately financed facilities at Chek Lap Kok,
including cargo handling and aircraft maintenance, got off to a flying
start with key awards for design work going mainly to British firms.
One of the biggest schemes is the $1bn construction of the world's
largest air cargo complex by Hong Kong Air Cargo Terminals. Work
involves a six-storey main building totalling 274,000 sq m and a 46,000
sq m two-storey express cargo centre.

The lead building consultant is Ove Arup who are working in tandem with
Foster Asia as the architectural sub-consultants. British Steel (Asia)
is to supply 53,550 tonnes of steel piles for foundations specialist
Franki Contractors, owned by Germany's Bilfinger & Berger. The main
construction is being done by Hong Kong's Gammon Construction, which is
jointly owned by Trafalgar House and Jardine Pacific.

Cathay Pacific Catering Services (CPCS) has chosen Scott Wilson
Kirkpatrick as the structural and civil consultants for its $200m in-
flight catering facility, one of three planned at the airport. Other
consultancy awards for the 56,000 sq m three-storey building include US
engineers, Parsons Brinckerhoff Asia who are acting as the mechanical
and electrical consultants and local firms Davis Langdon and Seah who
have been appointed as the quantity surveyors and Wong Tung & Partners
are the architects. The foundations will be undertaken by the local
firm, Shui On.

Six contractors - Dragages (French), Paul Y/Downer, Gammon, Hsin Chong,
Hip Hing and Shui On (all Hong Kong) - are having their bids for the
main building contract evaluated by the CPCS project team which hopes
to award the contract in January.

The facility is one of three in-flight kitchens planned at CLK. Others
will be build by LSG-Lufthansa Sky Chefs and Switzerland's Gate Gourmet
International, although consultants are only just being appointed.

The next key project is a $435m headquarters and hotel development for
Cathay Pacific Airways. The architects are Llewelyn-Davis with Harris
and Sutherland acting as structural consultants and Widnell as the
quantity surveyors. Bids for the foundations will be invited early next
year. The construction work, which has been split into four phases,
includes a 10-storey, 69,000 sq m reinforced concrete frame, glass
curtain wall clad office building and a 25-storey, 23,000 sq m, 500 bed
staff hotel.

Other private facilities include a second air cargo centre which is
planned by Asia Air Freight Terminals - a joint venture comprising
mainly Singaporean companies. The main consultants on the 22,000 sq m
scheme are Jones Lang Wootton Building Consultancy. The Hong Kong firm,
Liang Peddle Thorp are the architects, but the client has refused to
name the other firms involved. Piling contractors have just been asked
to prequalify.

There has been a reluctance by Hong Kong Aircraft Engineering, the
company undertaking aircraft maintenance, to name the professional team
who will advise on a massive hanger capable of handling three jumbo
jets side by side.

Other projects are far less advanced. These include the aviation fuel
system awarded to Aviation Fuel Supply which is led by Cathay Pacific
Airways, aircraft line maintenance which will be undertaken by Pan Asia
Pacific Aviation Services and China Aircraft Services, a 600-bed
airport hotel franchised to Regal Hotels, and a freight forwarding
centre being developed by Sun Hung Kai Properties.



