<A NAME = "17"></A>Copyright
ASIAN INFRASTRUCTURE MONTHLY via NewsNet
January 1, 1996

BATAM AIRPORT IS UPGRADED TO RIVAL SINGAPORE

Indonesia has started construction of an aircraft maintenance facility
and upgraded the international airport on the island of Batam in a bid
to rival Singapore's Changi airport's role as an international flight
hub for the south-east Asian region. Batam island, which lies a few
kilometres south of Singapore, is being developed as an industrial and
tourist centre together with the Singapore government authorities. The
island's airport already serves as a centre for cargo traffic for
industrial estates located there.

Batam's Hang Nadim airport, controlled by the Indonesian government
through the Batam Industrial Development Authority, has had its runway
extended to 4km at a cost of about $217m. It can now accommodate wide-
bodied aircraft such as Boeing 747-400s.

Construction of an aircraft maintenance and services facility has also
started. PT BAM, or Batam Aircraft Maintenance, located adjacent to
Batam's airport, is scheduled to complete a hangar at a cost of Rp18bn
($7.9m) by the end of 1996. It is hoped that BAM's services will help
lure customers away from Singapore's Changi airport. The maintenance
facility is being built to handle different types of aircraft including
Boeing 737 jets, Fokker planes and Indonesian-built CN 235s. BAM is
majority-owned by Indonesian entities including the state-owned
aircraft manufacturing company, IPTN, and Sempati Air, a private
domestic airline controlled by one of President Suharto's sons.

However, Singapore Technologies Aerospace, a unit of the Singapore
government's Singapore Technologies, also has a 25 per cent stake in
BAM. Singapore Technologies Aerospace is originally believed to have
wanted to take a majority stake in the project, a move which was
opposed by Indonesia's minister for research and technology, Mr B.J.
Habibie. As chairman of the Batam Industrial Development Authority, Mr
Habibie is closely involved with the island's progress.

Batam's goal is to become an international aviation hub. Aviation fuel
is about 20 per cent less expensive on Batam than in Singapore.
However, Singapore's Changi airport controls flight information in
parts of Indonesian airspace, including Batam. The latter has been a
point of some friction between Indonesia and Singapore, although the
boundaries of flight information regions were revised in September 1995
when President Suharto made an official visit to Singapore.

Indonesia was given control of air traffic services over an additional
space stretching from south of its islands of Sumatra to the Natuna
islands in the South China Sea but Singapore's Changi airport retains
supervision of aircraft movements from airports in Batam and
neighbouring Bintan.

The Indonesian authorities want Batam's Hang Nadim airport to act as a
transit and connecting point for international flights. However,
Indonesian officials admit this is still a long way off. 'It is still
hard for international air carriers to transit at Hang Nadim, as the
flow of goods and passengers is still low,' the director general of air
transportation, Mr Zainuddin Sikado, was quoted as saying in the
Jakarta Post. 'The most important thing will be how Batam improves the
quality of its services.'

Currently, there are no international flights to Batam, although eleven
domestic flights connect Batam to other airports throughout the
Indonesian archipelago. Local press reports said that by the end of
1999 twelve additional domestic routes are due to be served from Hang
Nadim.



<A HREF ="#HeadList">Back to Headline List</A><BR>
