<A NAME = "19"></A>Copyright
ASIAN INFRASTRUCTURE MONTHLY via NewsNet
January 1, 1996

THAILAND: BTS MASS TRANSIT OWNERSHIP IS RESTRUCTURED

Tanayong, the concessionaire for Bangkok's elevated rail transit, will
issue $160m worth of secured bonds as part of a shareholder
restructuring, as doubts continue to grow over its financial status.
The listed real estate firm reported in a mandatory stock market filing
that details of the issue price, collateral and launch time would be
released at a later date.

Talks have also opened with Thai-based Siam Commercial Bank on a
planned mobilisation of $562m from local capital markets, which will
form the core of financing for the $1.7bn project. It has already
secured a $50m loan from the International Finance Corporation and
hopes to raise a further $424m from KFW of Germany. 'We understand
contracts for the loans will be signed around the end of the year
(1995) and payment will be made in full to contractors shortly
afterwards,' said a banking executive.

Piling work on the 24km Bangkok Transit System railway began a year ago
but Tanayong has yet to come up with a funding package. Primarily a
developer of low-cost housing estates, it has been heavily affected by
a downturn in the property market and is regarded as having virtually a
zero credit rating. Bangkok Bank resigned as financial adviser earlier
this year after declining to guarantee a loans package. Its
replacement, Siam Commercial Bank, is insisting on a shareholder
restructuring that will bring in equipment suppliers and contractors on
an equity basis.

Italian-Thai Development, the sole construction contractor, has not
been paid since work started, and is expected to hold a 10 to 15 per
cent stake. 'The construction cost of the BTS skytrain is around Bt4m-
Bt5m ($160,000-$200,000) a month. We have received only Bt200m ($8m)
from Tanayong, while the value of work completed is around Bt1.86bn
($74.4m),' said company president, Premchai Karnsauta.

Siemens, the main equipment supplier, and Siam Commercial are expected
to be the other shareholders. Tanayong has agreed to reduce its stake
to 60 per cent, after attempts to push it into a minority role were
thwarted by contractual obligations. This will block efforts to raise
cash by listing the project on the stock exchange, as market rules
require a larger public shareholding. However, another attempt will be
made to diminish Tanayong's stake when its four-year concession
expires.

A Siam Commercial spokesman confirmed that 10 financial institutions
had been approached to join the domestic loans deal, which the bank
will guarantee in the absence of security from Tanayong. The local
package replaced earlier plans for an issue of US Yankee bonds that was
scuttled by bank worries over foreign exchange fluctuations.

Any further delays in putting together a loans package will almost
certainly force a halt in work on the mass transit, which depends
heavily upon the patience of Italian-Thai. About 12 per cent of the
piling work has been finished. 'We will continue to do advance work for
BTS in the next year. That is, we will wait until BTS is ready to pay,'
said Premchai, 'obviously Italian-Thai cannot be expected to continue
on the present basis.' The construction firm is issuing Bt4.9bn ($196m)
worth of bonds to pay for its shares acquisition.



