January 1, 1996

GOVERNMENT RECEIVES OECF LOAN FOR MASS TRANSIT

Japan's Overseas Economic Co-operation Fund (OECF) has approved a $200m
low-interest loan for the Bangkok subway project, providing the first
cash injection for the mass transit. Metropolitan Rapid Transit
Authority (MRTA) director, Theerapong Attajarusit, said a contract
would be signed in the second half of next year for the loan, which
will help pay for civil construction work. It will carry interest of
2.7 per cent with a seven-year grace period.

The government is paying for 80 per cent of the cost of the 21km
railway, with the remaining equity coming from equipment suppliers.
Consultants were due to complete a blueprint for the scheme in December
and formal bids for the construction are expected to be called by
February. A shortlist of eligible contractors, chosen from 28 consortia
that sought pre-qualification status in October, will be released
shortly before bidding starts.



