January 1, 1996

HOPEWELL SEEKS OFFSHORE LOANS TO RAISE FINANCE

Hopewell Holdings will try to raise $2.16bn from offshore loans to
finance its stalled elevated mass transit, after receiving government
assurances that the scheme would not be scrapped - yet.

Project co-ordinator, Anusak Intharapuwasak, confirmed that the group
was holding talks with Hongkong and Shanghai Bank Citibank and Mitsui
Trust and Banking for two-thirds of the funding needed for the $3.2bn
project. The remaining funds will come from Hopewell itself. 'The
negotiations are expected to be concluded early next year (1996). These
talks are still going on because Hopewell has just received the
construction designs, which have to be presented to the creditors,' he
said.

Transport Minister, Wan Muhammad, earlier granted Hopewell another two
months to show definite progress on the scheme, amid speculation that
it would be scrapped. He said that unspecified action would be taken
against the firm if it failed to meet the deadline, citing a two-year
delay in completion of the first phase. 'We will decide at that time
what steps can be taken, including the possible cancellation. But at
present we hope that won't be necessary,' he said.

The project was approved five years ago as a multi-level combination of
expressways and railways built above an old freight train line, but has
since made little progress. The Hong Kong firm blames the government
agencies' delays in handing over land holdings and ironing out design
problems, while the government charges that the contract was poorly
devised.

Originally intended to extend 60km, the route is likely to be reduced
by at least one-third because of obstructions that cannot be cleared.
Anusak said the first stage, from Don Muang airport to Yommarat in
central Bangkok, was due to be completed in early December, but only 7
per cent of the work had been carried out. Hopewell now plans to finish
a tollway covering all three phases in time for the 1988 Asian Games,
and the remaining work two years later.

But a transport ministry adviser, Gun Nagamati, said this deadline
would be almost impossible to meet because detailed designs for the
route were incomplete. 'There are conflict points with four expressway
routes that have to be resolved and no one has decided who will pay for
the additional construction costs from the necessary design changes.
This will take a further 12 months to sort out,' he said. Hopewell is
reported to be seeking a buyer for 25 per cent of the project (AIM,
December 1995/p14).



