<A NAME = "22"></A>Copyright
ASIAN INFRASTRUCTURE MONTHLY via NewsNet
January 1, 1996

INDIA IS UNLIKELY TO USE WORLD BANK LOAN FOR ROADS

A $206m World Bank loan for upgrading sections of the Delhi-Calcutta
highway may not be used by the surface transport ministry. This is
because it is unable to provide 25 to 30 per cent of the loan's annual
release from its own resources. For this fiscal year the budget for
roads is just Rs3.66bn ($105m), which is not even sufficient to repair
the existing roads.

The surface transport ministry feels that unless the finance ministry
gives it an additional grant for these counterpart provisions, it will
not be able to draw on the World Bank loan. Once the ministry commits
itself to drawing the loan it has to pay commitment fees, even if it
does not finally draw on the loan. The proposed loan was the third
tranche of the World Bank loan for Indian highways. It was meant for
widening and building bridges along the 1,100km Delhi-Calcutta national
highway. After feasibility studies and the project reports global
tenders are normally called for.

The second tranche of $200m has been partly used for the national
highways projects in six states - Punjab, Haryana, Orissa, West Bengal,
Madhya Pradesh and Maharashtra. Of the $200m, only half the amount has
so far been used mainly because the ministry of surface transport was
unable to get the counterpart funds.



<A HREF ="#HeadList">Back to Headline List</A><BR>
<HR>
<A NAME = "23"></A>Copyright
ASIAN INFRASTRUCTURE MONTHLY via NewsNet
January 1, 1996

JNPT INVITES BIDS FOR CONTAINER TERMINAL

The latest privatisation plans of the Jawaharlal Nehru Port Trust
(JNPT), across the harbour from Bombay, began with the port authorities
inviting tenders for two container berths. The new berths are expected
to cost between $150m and $180m, and will be tendered for on a build-
operate-transfer (BOT) basis for 20 years.

The tenders will have a technical bid and a financial bid. The
technical bids will include 'concept plans' as spelled out in the bid
documents. The financial bid will have to specify a one-time down
payment as a license fee, the royalty on each container handled and
guarantee a minimum annual throughput of containers. If this is not met
the contract would be in default. Only if the technical bids are
accepted will the financial bids be opened. After 20 years the two
container berths and ancillary facilities will revert back to the JNPT
at a depreciated value defined in the tender document.

The qualifying criteria for bids are as follows:

- companies must have over three year's experience of operating and
managing marine container terminals with an annual throughput of
500,000 TEU or more, using state-of-the-art equipment. Average
productivity of quayside cranes over three years of continuous actual
operations must be over 20 moves per hour;

- the average annual turnover of the bidders over the past three years
should be over $100m and paid-up capital of the company registered by
the bidders should be over $33m;

- the bidders should have adequate experience in the marketing and
development of international seaborne trade and sufficient expertise
available for efficient operation of a port-related container freight
station;

- the bidders need not have an Indian partner but the party finally
selected will have to be registered in India.

The tenders are to be submitted by April 19, 1996, and will be awarded
by the end of 1996. Work should be completed within three years. Mr
Shukla, port planning and development manager at the JNPT, expects the
bids will interest the 15 to 20 companies world-wide which have the
experience.

JNPT TENDER DETAILS:

The sale of bid documents will be from December 26, 1995 to January 15,
1996 on payment of Rs20,000 by demand draft payable to 'Jawaharlal
Nehru Port Trust'. The documents can be purchased from the Bombay
office of the JNPT at either:

1107, Raheja Centre, FPJ Marg, Nariman Point, Bombay 400 021. Tel: +91
22 2842733/2832458; or

Port Office: Administration Building, Jawaharlal Nehru Port Trust,
Sheva, New Bombay 400 707. Tel: +91 22 7242623/7242632.

Important dates:                                      1996

Review of bid document by bidders:             13 February
Bidders to seek clarification:               4 March, 1996
Pre-bid visit to JNPT:                         5 & 6 March
Pre-bid meeting:                               5 & 6 March
Further clarifications/queries by bidders:        16 March
Last date for submission for bids:          19 April, noon
Opening of technical bids:                   19 April, 3pm
Earnest money deposits on submission of bids:        Rs10m

The scope of the work involves the construction of two berths with a
total length of 450m to the north of the existing three container
terminals, and the development of container yards on 20ha of land to
store 15,000 to 20,000 containers. The two new berths are expected to
have a throughput of 470,000 TEU in the sixth year of operation. In the
last fiscal year (1994-95) the three existing container terminals of
the JNPT handled 240,000 TEU which is expected to go up to 400,000 TEU
by 1996-97. The berths should take third generation container ships of
12m draft. The minimum equipment required will be four cranes for
berths, each costing around $30m to $32m and capable of 70,000 to
80,000 moves a year, 10 cranes in the yard, and two cranes in the
railway yard. Similarly successful bidders must have operated quayside
cranes for three years with an average productivity of not less than 20
moves an hour, whilst the present highest crane productivity at JNPT
has been 12.2 moves an hour.

At present the turnaround time for container ships at JNPT is under 48
hours and containers lie in their yards for an average of one week. The
operating efficiency of the new container berths will have to be
considerably higher if they are to meet the throughput requirements of
JNPT.

Earlier plans for privatising the existing three container berths met
with political opposition and were dropped by the surface transport
ministry which is responsible for ports in the country.

Shukla says that the environmental clearance for five berths at a new
chemical terminal is expected to be passed within a couple of months.
Tenders for building the chemical berths and supporting facilities on a
BOT basis will follow soon after. When approved, this new terminal,
south of the existing bulk terminal at JNPT will boost the port's
capacity considerably. Shukla expects the chemical terminal to be
handling around 18m tonnes of bulk chemicals in another decade, making
it the largest in the country. For the moment, however, action is
centred on the bids for the container berths.



<A HREF ="#HeadList">Back to Headline List</A><BR>
<HR>
<A NAME = "24"></A>Copyright
ASIAN INFRASTRUCTURE MONTHLY via NewsNet
January 1, 1996

TENDERS ARE INVITED FOR ENNORE PORT PROJECT

Under an Asian Development Bank (ADB)-aided project, the new Ennore
port project of the Madras Port Trust has invited prequalification
tenders. The tenders are open to contractors from eligible member
countries of the ADB. The Ennore port is being built to handle coal,
and the prequalification tenders are preliminary to the actual bidding
for the works. The major works for which tenders have been invited are:

- dredging of the entrance channel and port basin of Ennore;

- construction of a wharf; and

- the construction of two breakwaters totalling 4km.

For the dredging works, approximately 9.7m cu m of sand and clay will
have to be removed from the port basin to a depth of 15.5m and another
3.2m cu m from the entrance channel. The contractors will have to
supply all the dredging, pumping, and earthmoving equipment and will
have to dispose of the dredged material within 5km of the site.

The construction of the wharf for coal unloading will be 550m by 26m in
water depths ranging from 3m to 7m. There will also be the construction
of three small jetties and the building of three approach bridges, one
to each jetty from the southern breakwater access road.

The two breakwaters will have a total length of 4km and will be of the
rubble mount type. The works involve underwater compaction of sand,
dumping of rocks supplied by the Madras Port Trust at onshore sites,
casting concrete Accropode armour units and placing them on the
breakwaters, and building an access road on the breakwaters. (Further
details are provided in the 'Tenders' section on page 31.)

The prequalification forms are available on payment of $50, from:
The Project Director
Ennore Port Project,
Madras Port Trust,
Centenary Building,
Rajan Salai,
Madras 600 001

Fax: +91 44 561228, Telex 041-8331.

The prequalification forms must be returned before 16 February, 1996.



<A HREF ="#HeadList">Back to Headline List</A><BR>
<HR>
<A NAME = "25"></A>Copyright
ASIAN INFRASTRUCTURE MONTHLY via NewsNet
January 1, 1996

BIDS CALLED FOR KARACHI'S WORLD TRADE CENTRE

The communications ministry has thrown a spanner in the Karachi Port
Trust's (KPT) ambitious multi-million dollar project to build a World
Trade Centre in the port city of Karachi and has instructed the client,
Karachi Port Foundation (KPF), to invite bids instead of awarding the
$100m contract to Promet Engineering of Singapore. The directive was
issued to KPT and KPF after protests from the US World Trade Centre in
New York, which claimed that it has contractual and legal rights to
construct the centre.

The permanent secretary at the communications ministry, Sher Afghan
Khan, informed the KPT of the government's decision and asked it to
prepare tender documents and have them published in local and
international dailies. He said the lowest bidder who also fulfils the
requisite terms and conditions, and has a solid financial background,
should be given the chance to build the World Trade Centre in a joint
venture with the Karachi Port Foundation. The KPT says that it hopes to
float tenders by the end of December, 1995.

Promet Engineering was so convinced that it had won the contract that a
number of experts from the firm's Singapore office have visited Karachi
on several occasions, inspected the site of the project, and held
numerous meetings with officials of the KPT. A memorandum of agreement
was recently signed between Promet Engineering and the KPT, inter alia
development of a container terminal, entertainment and recreational
facilities, a T-head jetty, transhipment and other port-related
facilities at Karachi port. According to plans prepared by the Karachi
Port Foundation, the trade centre complex will comprise of office
blocks for shipping companies, insurance firms, banks and international
trade institutions.



<A HREF ="#HeadList">Back to Headline List</A><BR>
<HR>
<A NAME = "26"></A>Copyright
ASIAN INFRASTRUCTURE MONTHLY via NewsNet
January 1, 1996

FINAL AGREEMENT IS DUE TO BE SIGNED FOR MASS TRANSIT

Canada's SNC-Lavalin, in a joint venture with Turkey's STFA and
Pakistan's Adamjee, is to construct the $500m, 15.2km, Corridor I of
the much-delayed Karachi Mass Transit project. They will sign the
agreement with the client, Islamabad-based National Mass Transit
Authority (NMTA), on January 17, 1996, according to sources close to
the joint venture. They said the delay was caused due to the financial
close and minor 'hiccups'.

The consortium was issued with a letter of intent by NMTA in November.
The project will be built on a build-operate-transfer basis and will
take two years to complete. Work is scheduled to start in early 1996.
The NMTA has decided to finance $163m of the scheme from its own
resources after it got 'fed-up' by the World Bank's foot dragging. The
donor agency had promised to provide a loan for the project but found
'too many inconsistencies'. The route alignment has had to be changed
several times in order to avoid densely populated areas along the
route, which runs from Mereweather Tower to Sohrab Goth. Pakistan
Railways has issued a 'no-objection certificate' to NMTA to ward off
criticism from environmentalists.

Meanwhile, bids for Corridor II of the light rail scheme are scheduled
to be opened in January 1996, sources close to the government said. A
number of international companies are reported to have pre-qualified
but were not named.



<A HREF ="#HeadList">Back to Headline List</A><BR>
<HR>
<A NAME = "27"></A>Copyright
ASIAN INFRASTRUCTURE MONTHLY via NewsNet
January 1, 1996

CONTROVERSIAL WINNER FOR SUKKUR BRIDGE IS ANNOUNCED

Italy's Astaldi has a Rs1.5bn ($60m) contract to build the proposed new
Sukkur Bridge in Sindh province. The contract has upset China National
Overseas Engineering Corporation, a company owned by the Chinese
ministry of foreign trade and co-operation, which submitted the lowest
bid for the project at a bid price of Rs1.134bn ($33.1m).

Moreover, of the nine bids submitted to the National Highways Authority
(NHA), Astaldi's bid was the only one submitted after the deadline of
August 30, 1995. Referring to the late submission of the bid by the
Italian company, the consultants, Denmark's COWI Consult declared that,
'Astaldi's bid was brought to the meeting room (at the NHA head office)
at 11.20 am ... all bidders were asked whether they would accept the
bid from Astaldi. As none of the bidders had any objections, the bid
was accepted as being received in due time'. Industry sources say this
statement appears to be an attempt to obfuscate the real issue, since
it was not the other bidders' responsibility, but NHA's, to reject the
bid because it had been submitted late.

'The "Instructions to Bidders" in this regard were unequivocal and very
clear. But not only was Astaldi's bid opened along with those of the
eight other bidders, NHA has now decided to award the contract to the
Italian company, and that too, at a price that is a staggering Rs366m
($10.7m) more than the price quoted by China National Overseas
Engineering,' it added.

Industry sources say that this suggests that Astaldi must have some
very influential political connections indeed in Islamabad. They say
this perception gains further credence when the NHA comes up with
flimsy excuses to sideline China National's bid. NHA claimed that the
Chinese company did not have enough English-speaking staff and that its
bid was 'too low'.

In a letter to NHA, China National said, 'we are prepared to offer any
guarantees within the realm of internationally accepted construction
norms, and as defined in the contracts documents, to assure the
National Highways Authority of our intention to complete the project in
full compliance with the tender specifications and within the time
period stipulated'.

When the NHA invited pre-qualification applications from interested
firms to bid for the construction of the new Sukkur Bridge earlier in
1995, 35 companies applied. Of these, NHA pre-qualified only 15 to bid
for the project, which is being financed by the Manila-based Asian
Development Bank.

Of the 15 pre-qualified companies, only nine submitted bids. They were:

- China National Overseas Engineering Corporation - Rs1.134bn ($33m);

- Astaldi - Rs1.501bn ($44m);

- China Road and Bridge Corporation - Rs1.744bn ($51m);

- S. Korea's Daewoo Corporation - Rs1.745bn ($51m);

- Dogus Construction and Trading - Rs1.76bn ($51m);

- S. Korea's Daelim Industrial - Rs1.805bn ($53m);

- Turkey's STFA - Rs2.051bn ($60m);

- Chulas Rasool Doojin Nazir of Pakistan and S. Korea - Rs2.1bn ($61m);

- Tekser & Wayss & Freytag of Turkey and Germany - Rs2.491bn ($73m).



