COASTAL ROAD CONTRACT GOES TO IRANIAN CONSORTIUM

A consortium of Iranian construction companies led by Mostazafan-o-
Janbazan Foundation (MJF), is poised to win a Rs11.5bn ($440m) contract
to build a 650km coastal road linking Mekran division, Baluchistan
province with Karachi, according to acting communications minister,
Sher Afghan. He said the project will be jointly funded by both Iran
and Pakistan.

Sher Afghan said Islamabad would contribute some 60 per cent of the
money while the rest will be provided by the Iranian government. He
declined to name the donor agency with whom Pakistan was seeking funds
but said negotiations were 'almost complete'. He said the contract with
the Iranian companies will be signed in early January, and the
memorandum of understanding (MoU) for the joint venture project was
signed between the two countries on May 17, 1995. The completion is for
1998-99, he added.



