BOMBAY WATER SUPPLY PLANS

Plans are on the drawing board to double the water supplied to Bombay
from the present 2,600m litres a day (mld) by 2021. The Bombay
Municipal Corporation, the user agency, has plans for four lakes to
ease the water shortage in the city and plan for additional demand. Of
these the Shai dam project will bring in an additional 1,067 mld, the
Kalu project will bring an additional 570 mld, the middle Vaitarna
project 447 mld and the Gargai project another 455 mld. The first to be
taken up will be the Vaitarna project, which is expected to be ready in
seven years. The projects are expected to cost a total of Rs32bn
($915m), of which the corporation will contribute 40 per cent, while
the rest will come through borrowings from international agencies.



<A HREF ="#HeadList">Back to Headline List</A><BR>
<HR>
<A NAME = "56"></A>Copyright
ASIAN INFRASTRUCTURE MONTHLY via NewsNet
January 1, 1996

ADB LOAN FOR KARNATAKA

An $85m Asian Development Bank loan has been approved for urban
infrastructure in the state of Karnataka in southern India. The money
will be used to provide sanitation, better roads, industrial estates
and housing in the towns of Channapatna, Mysore, Ramanagaram and
Tumkur. Another loan of $20m will be given to the Housing Development
Finance Corporation which will offer housing loans in the four towns
covered under the project. The loans are for a period of 25 years, with
a five year grace period, and will carry interest based on the ADB's
pool-based variable lending rate which is currently 6.9 per cent.



<A HREF ="#HeadList">Back to Headline List</A><BR>
<HR>
<A NAME = "57"></A>Copyright
ASIAN INFRASTRUCTURE MONTHLY via NewsNet
January 1, 1996

BALI AIRPORT EXPANSION PLANS

Plans are under way to expand the current airport facilities at Ngurah
Rai international airport on Bali, the local Kompas Daily has reported.
It quoted Sudarsono, head of the state-owned airport administrator
Angkasa Pura I, as saying that the airport had about 140 aircraft
movements a day but that this could rise to 160 a day during holidays.
In 1994 4.3m passengers arrived or departed at the airport but this is
expected to rise to 4.5m in 1995, and 6.5m in 1998.



<A HREF ="#HeadList">Back to Headline List</A><BR>
<HR>
<A NAME = "58"></A>Copyright
ASIAN INFRASTRUCTURE MONTHLY via NewsNet
January 1, 1996

WATER NETWORK AGREEMENT SIGNED

The Salim Group, Indonesia's largest conglomerate, and PT Kekar
Plastindo, have signed an agreement with the state water authority PDAM
Jaya, to build a Rp2,000bn ($874m) network to channel drinking water in
Jakarta, reported the Media Indonesia newspaper. It quotes Syamsu
Romli, president of PDAM Jaya, as saying that the Jakarta provincial
government, which oversees PDAM Jaya, would retain rights on the
pricing policy, but the two companies would be given the rights to
operate the project.



<A HREF ="#HeadList">Back to Headline List</A><BR>
<HR>
<A NAME = "59"></A>Copyright
ASIAN INFRASTRUCTURE MONTHLY via NewsNet
January 1, 1996

NEW AIRPORT PLANNED ON WEST SUMATRA

A new airport is being planned on Indonesia's West Sumatra according to
the official Antara News Agency. It said a new airport is being planned
at Ketaping, 22km from Padang, West Sumatra's capital. The decision
follows the announcement that the current Tabing airport cannot
physically be expanded to meet the increasing demand. The latest
figures released by the state-owned PT Angkasa Pura II, which runs
Tabing airport, show that the passenger numbers almost doubled in the
decade up to the end of 1994 from 199,000 to 370,000 passengers.



<A HREF ="#HeadList">Back to Headline List</A><BR>
<HR>
<A NAME = "60"></A>Copyright
ASIAN INFRASTRUCTURE MONTHLY via NewsNet
January 1, 1996

PHATTANAKETPHOUDOI WINS ROADS CONTRACT

Phattanaketphoudoi Group, one of the few active Laotian construction
firms, was awarded a $100m contract for road improvements in Vientiane.
The government said it would seek foreign aid money for the work, which
is expected to take 20 months.



<A HREF ="#HeadList">Back to Headline List</A><BR>
<HR>
<A NAME = "61"></A>Copyright
ASIAN INFRASTRUCTURE MONTHLY via NewsNet
January 1, 1996

BAKUN DAM CONTRACT TO CLOSE

The main contract for the controversial Bakun dam is to close in the
middle of January. The work will include the building of the dam,
reservoir, power station and transmission lines. Sixteen companies have
submitted bids to date. The contract will be awarded in April and
construction will begin in June. The company has already awarded a
M$247m ($97m) contract to South Korea's Dong-Ah Construction and
Industrial to divert a river at the dam site in the rain forests of
Malaysia's Borneo state of Sarawak. German engineering company Lahmeyer
have been awarded the master planning contract for the dam which will
be the second largest in the world, after China's Three Gorges.



<A HREF ="#HeadList">Back to Headline List</A><BR>
<HR>
<A NAME = "62"></A>Copyright
ASIAN INFRASTRUCTURE MONTHLY via NewsNet
January 1, 1996

OIL STORAGE FACILITY OPENS

Far East Oil Terminal One has officially opened a 200,000 tonne oil
storage facility in Pasir Gudang. The terminal cost M$70m ($27.6m), and
will be used to store oil products - mainly diesel and fuel oil. It is
the product of a joint venture between Cosco Singapore and Far East Oil
Singapore (FEOSO). The new terminal aims to serve Cosco's fleet of
vessels moving in the region. According to Captain Wei Jia Fu, chairman
of Far East Oil Terminal and president of Cosco Singapore, all 200,000
tonnes of storage capacity is taken up by Far East Oil Terminal for its
own use.



<A HREF ="#HeadList">Back to Headline List</A><BR>
<HR>
<A NAME = "63"></A>Copyright
ASIAN INFRASTRUCTURE MONTHLY via NewsNet
January 1, 1996

SECURITY FEES TO BE LEVIED ON AIRLINES LANDING IN PAKISTAN

Security fees are to be levied on international and domestic airlines
landing in Pakistan next year, if the government gives its approval.
Pakistan's Airport Security Force will charge airlines a 'nominal fee'
per passenger, according to a Karachi airport official, talking to
Reuters.



<A HREF ="#HeadList">Back to Headline List</A><BR>
<HR>
<A NAME = "64"></A>Copyright
ASIAN INFRASTRUCTURE MONTHLY via NewsNet
January 1, 1996

KARAKORUM HIGHWAY CONTRACT

The state-owned Frontier Works Organisation (FWO) has a Rs160m ($4.7m)
contract to carry out an extension and improvement to the Karakorum
Highway. It is expected to pave the way for increased trade between
Pakistan and the nations of the Central Asian Republics. The highway
stretches about 806km from the town of Hasanabdal, some 45km from the
capital, Islamabad, to Khunjerab pass on the Pakistan-China border. The
height of the pass is 4,700m. The width of the road varies from 6.1m to
6.7m. The designed speed on the road varies from 65kph in the hilly
sections, falling to 50kph in the mountainous sections.



<A HREF ="#HeadList">Back to Headline List</A><BR>
<HR>
<A NAME = "65"></A>Copyright
ASIAN INFRASTRUCTURE MONTHLY via NewsNet
January 1, 1996

AIRPORT SECURITY REVIEW

Following US criticism of the Philippines' airport security, transport
secretary, Jesus Garcia, has called for an independent assessment of
the safety and security of its international airports. He said, 'to
prevent a chaotic situation, an independent third party body should be
allowed to undertake the assessment, and the findings respected by ICAO
(International Civil Aviation Organisation) members.'



<A HREF ="#HeadList">Back to Headline List</A><BR>
<HR>
<A NAME = "66"></A>Copyright
ASIAN INFRASTRUCTURE MONTHLY via NewsNet
January 1, 1996

ASIAN TERMINALS TO EXPAND PORT CARGO HANDLING FACILITIES

Port operator Asian Terminals (ATI) is investing 3.933bn peso ($97.2m)
to expand its port cargo handling facilities, it said in a statement
filed with the Board of Investments. ATI is 33 per cent held by P&O
Australia, which recently issued a statement saying that ATI will issue
150m shares to the public or 20 per cent on 25 December, 1995. They
will be issued at 5.10 peso and will raise about A$40m ($29.6m). All
Asia Capital and Trust, which is underwriting the deal, said the
offering price was pegged at 12.5 times the company's projected
earnings per share. P&O's holding will be diluted to about 26 per cent
following the issue. Asian Terminals is the exclusive handler of
international bulk cargo at the Port of Manila. It also expects to open
a $36m grains terminal in January in Mariveles in Bataan province, west
of Manila, which will be the first commercial grains terminal in the
Philippines. The company plans to expand its container and cargo
handling facilities in South Harbour, Manila's largest port, from
12.5ha to 17.7ha, to accommodate 700,000 containers by 1997, up from
the present 500,000. Containerised and non-containerised cargo passing
through South Harbour rose by 35.6 per cent and 12.3 per cent
respectively in 1994, while total trade in the Philippines rose by 20.2
per cent. The company is also interested in the government's port
development projects in other parts of the Philippines such as General
Santos, Cagayan do Oro and Davao in Mindanao in the south, Cebu in
central Philippines and Subic and Batangas on the main island of Luzon.



<A HREF ="#HeadList">Back to Headline List</A><BR>
<HR>
<A NAME = "67"></A>Copyright
ASIAN INFRASTRUCTURE MONTHLY via NewsNet
January 1, 1996

BECHTEL TO FORM JOINT VENTURE TO BUILD DAM NEAR MANILA

Bechtel Corporation of the US has announced plans to form a joint
venture with two Philippine conglomerates - San Miguel and House of
Investments - to build a $1.5bn dam in Antipolo, near Manila. Bechtel
Overseas has given a proposal to the state's Metropolitan Waterworks
and Supply System (MWSS) to supply an additional 1.7bn litres of water
a day to Manila. However, the government is awaiting the results of a
study by the International Finance Corporation to determine the best
way to solve Manila's water crisis.



<A HREF ="#HeadList">Back to Headline List</A><BR>
<HR>
<A NAME = "68"></A>Copyright
ASIAN INFRASTRUCTURE MONTHLY via NewsNet
January 1, 1996

MANILA ANNOUNCES NEW RULES FOR INNER-CITY VEHICLE USE

The Metro Manila Development Authority has announced new rules for
inner-city vehicle use. Private cars may only use the city streets on
alternate days unless they are carrying more than three occupants. Cars
with number plates ending with an odd number may use the roads on
Mondays, Wednesdays and Fridays. Cars with even number plates are
restricted to Tuesdays, Thursdays and Saturdays. Known as the 'odd-
even' plan, it has caused an outcry as many owners feel that odd
numbers are getting a better deal, as it includes three working days.



<A HREF ="#HeadList">Back to Headline List</A><BR>
<HR>
<A NAME = "69"></A>Copyright
ASIAN INFRASTRUCTURE MONTHLY via NewsNet
January 1, 1996

AYALA LAND COMMUTER RAIL SYSTEM IN MANILA

Property developer Ayala Land (ALI) has said it is considering
developing a commuter rail system in the southern part of Metro Manila.
ALI has signed an MoU with the government-owned Philippine National
Railway (PNR) to undertake a feasibility study on the proposed rail
system. The line will run from Tutuban in downtown Manila to the south
where Ayala has property projects. If the study is positive, ALI hopes
to revitalise the PNR's south rail service in co-operation with PNR.



<A HREF ="#HeadList">Back to Headline List</A><BR>
<HR>
<A NAME = "70"></A>Copyright
ASIAN INFRASTRUCTURE MONTHLY via NewsNet
January 1, 1996

HYUNDAI WINS CONTAINER TERMINAL CONTRACT

South Korea's Hyundai Engineering and Construction has won a $273m
order to take over the second phase of construction of the container
terminal at Pasir Panjang. It will be responsible for reclamation, soil
improvement and building the decking of the terminal. The works are due
to be completed by April, 2002.



<A HREF ="#HeadList">Back to Headline List</A><BR>
<HR>
<A NAME = "71"></A>Copyright
ASIAN INFRASTRUCTURE MONTHLY via NewsNet
January 1, 1996

FOUR FLYOVERS TO BE BUILT IN BANGKOK

Four flyovers will be built at key road junctions in Bangkok to relieve
congestion, with completion scheduled for mid-1997. A 750m two-lane
structure will be built outside Don Muang airport, a 500m two-lane
flyover at Bang Khen, a 475m one-lane flyover outside Kasetsart
University, and a small structure at Ratchavipa interchange. No cost
estimates were released.



<A HREF ="#HeadList">Back to Headline List</A><BR>
<HR>
<A NAME = "72"></A>Copyright
ASIAN INFRASTRUCTURE MONTHLY via NewsNet
January 1, 1996

UNITED COMMUNICATIONS WINS CCTV CONTRACT

United Communication Industry, a Thai-based company, will supply $5.2m
worth of closed circuit TV equipment to Bangkok Metropolitan
Administration for a traffic monitoring system. The national government
is providing 60 per cent of the funding under a transport upgrading
programme for Bangkok, and the BMA - loosely equivalent to a city
council - will cover the rest of the cost. A BMA spokesman said the
contract was for the second stage of a British-installed computer-
activated scheme that has already been installed at 16 key
intersections. Under stage two, a further 44 monitoring points will be
established. United Communication is contracted to finish installing
the TV equipment by early 1997.



<A HREF ="#HeadList">Back to Headline List</A><BR>
<HR>
<A NAME = "73"></A>Copyright
ASIAN INFRASTRUCTURE MONTHLY via NewsNet
January 1, 1996

TANK TERMINAL FINANCE

A $48m two-tranche, limited-recourse project financing deal for Thai
Tank Terminal is in syndication, said the arranger, ABN AMRO Bank. The
funds will be used to finance the construction of Phases II and III of
the tank terminal facilities at the Mab Ta Phut port. The $23m tranche
A, for Phase II, carries a maturity of eight years with an average life
of 4.8 years. The $25m tranche B, for phase III, carries a maturity of
nine years with an average life of six years. The margin for both is
150 basis points over the London Interbank Offered Rate. Repayment of
the facility will be in 16 semi-annual unequal instalments. Repayment
of tranche A will start in March 1996 and repayment of tranche B in
June 1997. Fees are 20 basis points for lead managers committing to $8m
or more and 15 basis points for managers committing to $4m or more.
(Reuters)



<A HREF ="#HeadList">Back to Headline List</A><BR>
<HR>
<A NAME = "74"></A>Copyright
ASIAN INFRASTRUCTURE MONTHLY via NewsNet
January 1, 1996

ASIAN DEVELOPMENT BANK TO FINANCE WASTEWATER PROJECTS IN BANGKOK

The Asian Development Bank has approved a $150m loan to partly finance
its wastewater management projects in one of the five provinces
comprising metropolitan Bangkok. The loan will be sourced from the
bank's ordinary capital resources which carries a variable interest
rate, currently standing at 6.91 per cent. The loan is repayable over
25 years and includes a grace period of five years. The project
involves the construction of wastewater collection and central
treatment facilities.



<A HREF ="#HeadList">Back to Headline List</A><BR>
<HR>
<A NAME = "75"></A>Copyright
ASIAN INFRASTRUCTURE MONTHLY via NewsNet
January 1, 1996

WORLD BANK APPROVES LOAN FOR HIGHWAY PROJECT IN THAILAND

The World Bank has approved a $150m loan for the Fifth Highway Sector
Project. The money will go towards improving the infrastructure of
Thailand's roads and paying for new environmental protection measures.
The project has three components. First, selected sections of the
country's major inter-urban national highways will be widened from two
lanes to four. Second, technical assistance and training will be given
to various transport-related government departments in air quality,
highway safety improvements and institutional development. Third, an
Environmental Assessment Unit will be established with the department
of highways to carry out proper assessments and propose mitigating
measures for all highway improvements and construction works.



<A HREF ="#HeadList">Back to Headline List</A><BR>
<HR>
<A NAME = "76"></A>Copyright
ASIAN INFRASTRUCTURE MONTHLY via NewsNet
January 1, 1996

VIETNAMESE BRIDGE OPENS

A bridge has been opened linking Hanoi with the major ports of Haiphong
and Quang Ninh in the north-east. It spans the Kinh Thay river and is
333m long. It is also hoped that the bridge will help tourism by
cutting travelling time between Hanoi and the northern resort of Ha
Long Bay from four hours to just two.



