September 30, 1996

George Town to diversify

from BUSINESS TIMES, The New Straits Times Press (Malaysia) Berhad,
     30 Sep 1996, page 7

By Ishun P. Ahmad

GEORGE Town Holdings Bhd expects to not only expand its current activities
but also to diversify into film studios, entertainment centres and theme
parks to ensure long-term growth.
  Chairman Tuanku Abdullah Ibni Almarhum Tuanku Abdul Rahman says in the
latest annual report that the RM204.75 million from the proceeds of its
rights issue in November 1995 were used to expand its overseas business
and its existing operations.
  He says George Town has acquired a project in Leavesden, north-west of
London, which will house England's first movie theme studio tour and
family entertainment complex, comparable with that of Universal Studio,
Disneyland, and Disneyworld.
  Reviewing its financial standing, he notes that George Town has posted a
slightly higher group pre-tax profit of RM12.33 million for the year ended
March 31 1996 compared to RM12.19 million in 1995. This is on the back of
a turnover of RM310.20 million compared to RM310.11 million previously.
  Profit after-tax before minority interest improved slightly to RM8.02
million compared to RM7.92 million previously.
  Directors are recommending a final dividend of eight per cent less tax
for the year just ended.
  During the year under review, George Town Chemist Sdn Bhd opened two
oulets, one each in Kuala lumpur and Port Klang, bringing its total to 25
in the Klang Valley.
                               

