BUSINESS TIMES (MALAYSIA) via NewsNet
September 30, 1996

Ariston to compensate land occupants in Sihanoukville project

from BUSINESS TIMES, The New Straits Times Press (Malaysia) Berhad,
     30 Sep 1996, page 20

By Leela Barrock in Phnom Penh

PHNOM PENH, Sun: Ariston Sdn Bhd has agreed to pay some US$400,000 (US$1 =
RM2.51) in compensation to 360 families who are occupying land on the site
of the Kang Keng airport and on Naga Island, in Sihanoukville.
  "We are paying the compensation on behalf of the Royal Government of
Cambodia, eventhough land is a state matter," Mr Tan Teng Chye, Ariston's
project director, said in Sihanoukville.
  Ariston, which was awarded the US$1.3 billion Sihanoukville development
project, was accused of dragging its feet in starting work on the project,
by several quarters, including Cambodian First Prime Minister Prince
Norodom Ranariddh.
  The Malaysian company explained that it was unable to begin renovation
work at the Sihanoukville International Airport - the first phase of the
project - as it was unable to obtain vacant possesion of the land.
  The amount that was paid to the various families is said to vary
according to the size of land each family lived or worked on.
  According to Tan, Ariston was advised on the amounts to be paid to the
villagers by a special task force within the Sihanoukville Development
Authority that was set up to determine the figure.
  According to the villagers and some of the provincial officials, the
cheques reportedly ranged from US$25 to more than US$3,000.
  However, Tan said Ariston has still not obtained vacant posession of the
land as the villagers are still on the land. "They should move off soon
and then we should be able to get things going," he told Business Times in
a telephone interview.
  Ariston has begun work on Naga Island, however, where an international
standard casino resort and hotel will be built.
  The deputy governor, Kim Bo, who witnessed the handing over ceremony,
said the villagers had arrived at a mutual understanding with the Royal
Government and were happy to accept the compensation.
  "I am aware that my land is located on a development site and I am happy
with the compensation," a villager was quoted as saying in a local
newspaper.
  He admitted that he was among those who had taken up weapons and
demonstrated at the airport site in May this year.
  "I thought that my land was being invaded by Ariston at the time and so
I took an axe to fight against them. But now I find they are honourable
and I am very happy with the compensation," he said.
  Neither Tan nor Cambodian officials would specify the amount of cash
that had been paid for each plot of land.
  However, Cambodian officials say the agreed compensation that was paid
by Ariston amounted to some US$1,500 for each hectare of land, though
other sources say US$1,700 was paid per hectare of land.
  Meanwhile, Ariston signed three agreements in mid-September with the
Royal Goverment that will expedite work on the Sihanoukville project.
  The first agreement was for the lease of land on Naga Island for a 70-
year period. Naga will be the site of an international standard hotel
resort and casino.
  The second was a land lease agreement for O Cheou Teal, involving the
development of an 18-hole international golf course and international
hotel.
  The third agreement was a 25-year build, operate and transfer (BOT)
concession agreement for the Sihanoukville International Airport.
                              

Copyright 1996 The New Straits Times Press (Malaysia) Berhad



