<A NAME = "22"></A>Copyright
BUSINESS TIMES (MALAYSIA) via NewsNet
September 30, 1996

Improved services with accountability

from BUSINESS TIMES, The New Straits Times Press (Malaysia) Berhad,
     30 Sep 1996, page 20

By Wendy Lim

THE corporatisation of the Standards and Industrial Research Institute of
Malaysia (Sirim) will be different from other such exercises undertaken by
the Government. This is because the role, contribution and viability of
Sirim will not be measured by its revenue-earning capacity.
  Sirim Bhd president and chief executive Dr Mohamed Ariffin Aton said its
corporatisation will allow a more flexible management system for it to
provide fast, efficient, cost-effective and customer-oriented services
with accountability.
  "Ultimately, we want to be cost effective and broaden our customer base
and train our people to make decisions at their level. This will certainly
speed things up but quality is maintained as they know their job well.
  "At the same time, everyone learns about responsibility and will be held
accountable for making that decision," he told Business Times in Shah
Alam.
  Ariffin was the managing director of Petronas Research Sdn Bhd before he
was appointed to head Sirim Bhd, taking over from Datuk Dr Ahmad Tajuddin
Ali who became the executive chairman of Tenaga Nasional Bhd,
  For Sirim to achieve quality and speed, Ariffin is embarking on an
"inside out" quality services strategy to meet its vision.
  He believes that quality, when planted internally, will progress
naturally outwards.
  "In our day-to-day work, for example, the finance department which holds
the traditionally role of scrutinising every claim will have to think of
its colleagues as clients.
  "Some think this will encourage forgery but the claimants have a
responsibility and are accountable for their claims.
  "In this way, there will be continuous improvement and value creation
for the company to move faster. Ultimately, Sirim is the people," Ariffin
said.
  Sirim's vision, he said, is to be a renowned institution in three of its
core businesses: research, technology development, and standardisation.
  His said his task is to strenghten the competency base and put in place
the research and development (R and D) strategy.
  Sirim's technology competencies include industrial instrumentation and
electronics, industrial automation, automotive, measurements and
artificial intelligence systems.
  Ariffin said R and D does not necessarily get one's hands dirty. "There
is also a management side to it which I am dealing with."
  He feels that R and D is a continuing process of investment and regards
researchers as "a special breed of people who are very independent".
  "It is an intellectually challenging experience to be in the group," he
said.
  Ariffin, who considers working as his pastime and thinking of solutions
as his hobby, feels that the biggest challenge in managing researchers is
to change their perception of research work as a service.
  "Research is not a hobby, especially when there is a sponsor, and
researchers must try to provide the quality work in as short a time as
possible within a limited budget," he said.
  On human resource management, Ariffin said he is not worried that
Sirim's staff will be pinched. "All good companies will have staff
movement. Those who move away from Sirim are not totally lost as they will
be contributing to the country in other ways."
                              

Pix: Ariffin ... obssessed with quality.

