BUSINESS TIMES (MALAYSIA) via NewsNet
September 30, 1996

Resolve problems within party, advises Dr M

from BUSINESS TIMES, The New Straits Times Press (Malaysia) Berhad,
     30 Sep 1996, page 1

By Jimmy Yeow

PRIME Minister and Barisan Nasional chairman Datuk Seri Dr Mahathir
Mohamad has urged members from the Barisan component parties not to go to
court to solve their internal disputes.
  He said while it is common to have differences in opinions between
members, they should try to resolve their problems within the party.
  Dr Mahathir said there will be no end to the culture of members seeking
legal action if members persist in doing so.
  "Today it will at the party's central committee level, tomorrow
divisional and branches."
  For example, he said even if a member succeeds in getting the court to
declare him or her as the party leader, it would not help if the majority
of the members reject his or her leadership.
  "There must be some form of compromise within the party.
  "If this cannot be achieved, the dispute should then be solved by the
political way of who is getting the most support from members," he told
reporters at the Sultan Abdul Aziz International Airport on his return
from New York yesterday.
  He was asked to comment on the political tussle between Parti Gerakan
president Datuk Seri Dr Lim Keng Yaik and Gerakan member and member of
Parliament for Batu, Datuk Joseph Chong.
  Dr Mahathir said the dispute within Gerakan will not affect the Barisan
coalition and expressed confidence that the Gerakan members will be able
to resolve their problem among themselves.
  On Umno, Dr Mahathir said the special committee, headed by him, to
investigate complaints against disciplinary committee members for
allegedly breaching the no-campaign ruling is keeping an eye on the
conduct of the candidates.
  "You will find out in time," he said to a question whether any of the
disciplinary committee member had breached the ruling.
  A total of 185 candidates has been declared eligible to contest in the
Umno party elections in October.
  On allegations that some candidates are using their official functions
as a  "platform to campaign" by opening two or three functions a day, the
Prime Minister said the bunching of some of these functions could not
avoided.
  "But I hope the delegates will be able to judge for themselves the
motives of these functions," Dr Mahathir said.
                               

