September 30, 1996

Smooth start for self-service at selected Caltex petrol stations

from BUSINESS TIMES, The New Straits Times Press (Malaysia) Berhad,
     30 Sep 1996, page 2

SELF-service for motorists at Caltex Oil petrol stations seems set to have
a smooth introduction with the company offering self-serve educational
programmes for motorists at three sites.
  The three selected petrol stations, located in the Klang Valley, have
been positioned with a group of trained experts known as customer service
assistants to help motorists get comfortable with the idea of serving
themselves.
  "We are committed towards addressing the labour issues that are plaguing
the country, especially with the issue of foreign labour at the
forecourts," chairman and managing director of Caltex Oil (M) Ltd, Mr.
Robert J. Gregory said in Kuala Lumpur.
  "As with any change, there is bound to be some apprehension and we
believe the best solution is to help, prepare and educate the public to
get used to the various aspects of self-service," he said.
  The Meor Hisham station in Ampang began to offer self-service on
September 19, followed by F I Star and Kwang Hap Siang.
  The company has put in place a programme that incorporates various on-
site programmes for motorists. This is to familiarise them with the
concept of self-serve well before the Government mandated date for all
petrol stations to be on self-service by January 1, 1997.
  Trained customer service assistants will point out how to use user
friendly electronic facilities and to guide customers on payment methods
according to their choice of cash or card.
  In addition, Caltex Malaysia will also have an elite squad of trained
personnal who will be deployed to these self-serve test stations initially
and subsequently to the various self-serve test stations in residential
neighbourhoods.
  Tagged as the "Self service Support Squad" (SSS Squad), the squad will
be commissioned to provide additional support to customer service
personnel at petrol stations and introduce the do-it-yourself concept
whilst giving hands-on demonstrations on self-serve.
  Apart from investing in mobile labour squads, Caltex has also invested a
total of RM9 million on hardware, electronic and retail automation for
facilitating self-serve.
  Caltex has also set up a toll-free hotline at 800-3188 to handle
enquiries on self-serve.
  "We are confident that with our comprehensive programme, additional
features and unique services, Caltex Malaysia will take the lead for self-
serve," said Gregory. "We will also be joining the Government and other
oil industry members in the joint educational programmes that have been
planned." he added.
                               

