VIETNAM: $650m for Vung Tau port

from BUSINESS VIETNAM, November 1, 1996

Saigon:

In the largest build-operate-transfer deal ever signed in Vietnam, a
Taiwanese led consortium  is to put up to $650m into turning Vung
Tau into the nation's leading container port.  The deal, involving
Taiwan's Evergreen, Malaysia's MMC Ports, and Singapore's Tredia
Resources, is the largest infrastructure investment on record.
Under the BOT contract the consortium will run the port for 40
years before handing it back to the government.

A first phase is expected to go into operation within two years and
with 15 years the project will have the capacity to handle 45
million tonnes of cargo annually.

Vietnam Marine Corporation, a state-owned entity, will initially
hold a 5 per cent stake in the project but as the expansion starts
to make money it will buy shares from its foreign partners to
increase this to up to 20 per cent.

The Vung Tau upgrade will complement the $40m revamp of Saigon
Port.  The ADB funded project will see capacity there expanded by
25% by 1998.

With annual trade growing at 30% Vietnam's ports are woefully inadequate
to handle it.  They could become completely congested within two
years as new infrastructure development fails to keep pace with
trade.

Vietnam has a BOT law to encourage infrastructure improvements but
few companies have attempted this form of investment because of
limited guarantees on foreign exchange and pricing of services.

Copyright 1996 Business Vietnam




