BUSINESS VIETNAM via NewsNet
November 1, 1996

Cambodia downsizes contract

from BUSINESS VIETNAM, November 1, 1996

Phnom Penh:

Cambodia has a unique interpretation of downsizing, the American
term for reducing employees.  Cambodia downsizes entire contracts.
Two years ago it threw out two Thai airlines and signed with the
Malaysians for Royal Air Cambodge.  A year ago Phnom Penh signed a
billion dollar deal with Malaysian company YTL to turn Angkor Wat
into a major tourist attraction.  Now, the land that had been
awarded to YTL (1095 hectares) has been cut in half and seven new
companies have been called in to bid on its development.

Aspara, the agency charged with overseeing protection and
management of the temples, has asked two local companies and five
foreign firms including France's Dumen GTM Cambodge, and Korea's
Daewoo.  YTL was not even on the list.

The rebidding for the Angkor Wat complex reveals the infighting
between Tourism Minister Veng Sereyvuth who supported YTL, and
State Minister Van Moulyvann who leads Aspara.  The latter had been
particularly critical of YTL's proposals for a light-and-sound
show, while conservationists are worried that the hotels will be
built on archaeologically protected land.

For his part Veng Sereyvuth defended YTL saying that it had
produced a professional plan that would protect the environment and
had commissioned a study showing the light-and-sound show would not
damage the temples.

The real question that investors are asking on their Cambodian
deals is whether a Cambodian contracts is worth the paper it is
written on.  The YTL downsizing is an obvious example that its not.

