VIETNAM: British may get a chance

from BUSINESS VIETNAM, November 1, 1996

Hanoi:

British construction firm John Liang International may yet get the
chance to build Hanoi's new international airport.  Four years ago
it had submitted a bid for a new, smaller passenger terminal after
undertaking a privately financed feasibility study that assessed
passenger growth and traffic forecasts.  The British firm, despite
strong backing from London, lost the Hanoi contract to a Japanese
construction group and work on the first phase of the Hanoi
rebuilding scheme, the construction of a new international
passenger terminal, has just begun.

The Vietnamese, never slow to use foreign cash to achieve their own
goals, have decided that the new Hanoi airport would serve both
civilian and military aircraft.  Japanese aid is given under strict
civilian guidelines and is specifically prohibited from being used
to assist military - related projects.  This means that the
Japanese will most likely withdraw from the project altogether.  If
that happens, the most likely beneficiary will be John Liang
International that still has the original ,50m in government aid
that was used to back its earlier bid.  Talks have been opened and
the Vietnamese are receptive to a British takeover should the
Japanese falter.

The Hanoi revamp, plus a similar one in Saigon, are the
cornerstones of a massive upgrading scheme.  The country's civil
aviation department has proposed spending $5 billion to $8 billion
during the next 15 years to improve 50 airports throughout the
country.

An IATA report has predicted that air traffic in Vietnam would grow from
1.2 million passengers in 1993 to 3.9 million in 2000 and 17.4
million by 2010.

