VIETNAM: Following in thou footsteps

from BUSINESS VIETNAM, November 1, 1996

Hanoi:

As Westralian Sands executives fled their Ha Tinh ilmenite mine
with little more than the shirts on their backs, and leaving behind
40 containers of sophisticated mining equipment that was
subsequently stolen by provincial authorities, another Australian
company was digging in for the long term.

Perth based Golden Tiger Resources is one of the few publicly
listed firms in Australia to focus entirely on Vietnam.  "Our company is
now completely set up to become a mining company in Vietnam,"
Golden Tiger Resources managing director Rupert Crowe said.  "It is
going to take a while, but we have confidence that there is a lot
to be found there."

Two of Golden Tiger's Vietnam's projects are 50-50 joint ventures with
the Canadian mining company Teck Corp.  Golden Tiger has three
exploration programmes under way in Vietnam.  Two are joint ventures
with Teck to search for gold, and the other is a lead-zinc project.

With reference to Hanoi's theft of 40 containers of mining
equipment, Crowe said, "Obviously, there are concerns about those
sort of problems.  But our relationship with the Vietnamese is very
good." Westralian said much the same thing, right up until the
police put a padlock on their mine.

