BUSINESS VIETNAM via NewsNet
November 1, 1996

VIETNAM: Sponsorship opportunities abound

from BUSINESS VIETNAM, November 1, 1996

Hanoi:

In Indochina, there are great opportunities for sponsorship, but a
lot of thought must be given to the realities of each country
before events are planned, according to Bates Vietnam chairman
David Bell.

Mr Bell said it is believed that consumer involvement in events is
stronger in the developing markets of Indochina because consumers
have been isolated from international-style events for a long time.

"In the case of Vietnam, it's about 20 years.  therefore, virtually
anything new is exciting," said Mr Bell.

However, because of the rigid system of government control in some
countries, it does not mean that all sponsorships will
automatically be a success.

In Vietnam, there is a three-station TV Choice in Saigon and Hanoi,
and the station calculates its rate on time segments rather than
programming.

"TV cost efficiency is generally good.  However, one of the major
problems is the inability of the TV Stations to plan their
programming in advance and their likelihood to change," said Mr
Bell.

"Viewers may get used to a foreign entertainment programme being on
at a certain time each week, but suddenly it will change and much
viewership is lost."

In Burma, only the state-run TV Station gives national coverage and
reaches a total audience of around three to four million viewers.
A peak time 30-second spot goes for $585, so for high rating
programmes, Myanmar TV is very economical.

According to Mr Bell, sponsorship is not well developed in
Cambodia, but it is possible to do it.  He explained that the Thai
station, TV5, is easier to deal with and has better coverage - with
spillover into Cambodia.  The Thais are also more clued up about
sponsorship.  However, it is more expensive for a peak time spot,
and no reliable research is used to evaluate performance.

All these three countries have marked differences in cultural
values.  They have different religions and languages, though there
are some common languages such as English, Chinese, French and Thai.

"The trend for marketing events in these countries is to use local
languages," said Mr Bell.

"Nevertheless, some important similarities, like sport, music,
entertainment programmes and popular sciences, are such that
sponsorship and event marketing can use them for regional
activities that can reach similar groups across differing cultures.

"Though there are a lot of problems we have to face in organising
sponsorships and event marketing in these markets, we should try
new things and have patience with the authorities and other
logistical problems."

