November 1, 1996

LAOS: Lao runaround on telecom deal

from BUSINESS VIETNAM, November 1, 1996

Vientiane:

Doing business in Indochina is never easy but the runaround given
to Thailand's Shinawatra telecoms group was more frustrating than
most.  Three times it flew its executives and media reps into
Vientiane in anticipation of the contract signing.  The first
postponement was due to only a Lao version of the contract being
available.  The Lao's inexplicably gave as their reason for the
delay a requirement for an English version of the contract.

The second postponement was due to the arrival in Vientiane of
Thailand's Prime Minister which gave Lao government officials a
much better excuse to be unavailable.  The third postponement
underlined the reasons for the first delay.  Vientiane had been
offered a better deal by M Group, another Thai telecom giant which
has a high profile in Laotian telecommunications.

M Group has won a licence from the Lao government to operate a
gigantic broad-casting satellite project, L-Star.  The country's
first satellite will be put into orbit in December next year and
will cover all of Asia.

Shinawatra operates Thaicom satellites of similar coverage and
capacity.  The top bosses at both groups are widely known to have
had a difficult relationship for the past few years.  Suradet
Mukyangkoon, a highly-placed source in the Lao government said the
postponements were caused merely by a Thai company wishing to
participate in the telecom projects.

"The company has approached the government and made attractive
offers many times while Shinawatra was engaged in negotiating to
work out the new deal," said the government source, without naming
the contender.

The message to investors is clear.  If negotiating in Indochina in
good faith, you can bet on it that the other side isn't.  If the
other side comes up with a litany of excuses to avoid signing a
contract, look over your shoulder.  You will probably find the
competition using every trick in the book to get you out of the
picture.

