BUSINESS VIETNAM via NewsNet
November 1, 1996

CAMBODIA: Caltex aims for 10%

from BUSINESS VIETNAM, November 1, 1996

Phnom Penh:

It's been 21 years since Caltex was last in Cambodia.  The US oil
giant has re-entered the Cambodian market on a wave of confidence
starting with the first American owned retail outlet since 1975.

Caltex has plans to invest $20m in Cambodia, opening some 20
service stations in Phnom Penh and major provincial cities and
building a major oil depot at Sihanoukville.

"We see great potential here," said Clifton Hon, chairman of the
Caltex Group of Companies based in Singapore.

He said studies indicated that Cambodia's current
11,000-barrel-per-day consumption of petroleum products could more
than quadruple in the coming decade if its economy develops along
the lines of its neighbours.

"We're hoping for at least a 10% market share very quickly," said
John Raeside, the general manager of Caltex Cambodia Ltd.

Five other Caltex stations are now under construction in the
capital and the company is looking at sites to build on in
Cambodia's second-largest city of Battambang and in the populous
east-central province of Kampong Cham.

The service stations will eventually be supplied by the $8m
Sihanoukville depot which will handle oil from Caltex refineries in
Singapore and Thailand.

The depot is expected to be completed in mid-1997 and until then
products will be shipped up the Mekong River to the port in Phnom
Penh.

Copyright 1996 Business Vietnam




<A HREF ="#HeadList">Back to Headline List</A><BR>
