China: 20 Import Items to Be Under Compulsory Check-up

from CHINA BUSINESS INFORMATION NETWORK (CBnet), Sep. 25, 1996

Beginning on October 1, 20 import items will be listed for compulsory
examination by the China Commodity Inspection Bureau (CCIB).

In the future, only those commodities bearing CCIB license labels may
be imported, according to CCIB sources.

On September 4, 1995, CCIB and the State Foreign Economic and Trade
Commission issued a circular that named the second group of commodities
affected by the safety and quality licensing system.

The 20 items include washing machines, vacuums, appliances for grooming
hair and skin, electric water heaters, electric ovens, microwave ovens,
electric pots, electric irons, electric food processors, fluid heaters,
videotape recorders, audio equipment, personal computers, monitors,
switch-mains, printers, electric tools, low-voltage electric appliances
and electric welding machines.

Since the circular was issued, CCIB has received more than 800
applications from over 180 factories based in 27 foreign countries and
regions. So far, CCIB has issued over 500 safety and quality licenses
to these applicants.

