<A NAME = "26"></A>Copyright
CHINA BUSINESS INFORMATION NETWORK via NewsNet
September 25, 1996

China: Nujiang River Canyon gains growing popularity among tourists

from CHINA BUSINESS INFORMATION NETWORK (CBnet), Sep. 25, 1996

China's Nujiang River Canyon, known as the "Grand Canyon of the Orient"
 has become a hot tourist attraction as increasing travelers and
adventurers swarm in.

Located in the west of Yunnan Province, southwest China, the Nujiang
River Canyon is grand and steep because of the swift Nujiang River, the
perilous Biluo Mountain and the Gaoligong Mountain on each bank of the
river.

The Yunnan section of the Nujiang River Canyon is 621 kilometers long
and 3,000 meters deep, as compared with the Grand Canyon in Colorado
which is 440 kilometers long and 1,839 meters deep.

Tourists visiting the Nujiang Grand Canyon can not only see the canyon
itself, but can also be exposed to the rich ethnic culture and folklore
of the local Lisu, Bai, Nu, Dulong, Jingpo and Tibetan ethnic groups.

The primeval forests, waterfalls and rivers are also tourist
highlights.

Thanks to modern highways, it takes 10 hours for tourists to get to the
canyon from Kunming, the provincial capital.

Last year, over 194,000 Chinese and overseas tourists visited the
canyon.

Copyright 1996 China Business Information Network




