China: Qian Qichen urges EU to support China"s entry into WTO

from CHINA BUSINESS INFORMATION NETWORK (CBnet), Sep. 25, 1996

Chinese Vice Premier and Foreign Minister Qian Qicheng Monday urged the
European Union to take more active steps to support China's efforts in
entering the World Trade Organization.

He made this remark during his meeting with his counterpart of the
European Union in New York.

Qian pointed out that in recent years the overall relationship between
China and EU is developing in a good direction.

He said China values the important role the EU and its members are
playing in the international affairs and wishes to develop friendly and
co-operative relationship with them.

On economic and trade relations, Qian said there is great potential for
development since the two sides are economically complementary.

He said China will continue the process of opening up to the outside
world and liberalizing its trade practices.

He called upon the EU countries to take more positive steps in
eliminating protective trade barriers against Chinese products and to
take positive and concrete measures on the questions of China's entry
into the World Trade Organization.

Irish Foreign Minister Dick Spring, the current EU president, told Qian
that EU is determined in pursuing the long-term policy of developing
strategic relationship with China.

Noting the dialogue between China and EU has already had a good
beginning, Dick said that the EU is willing to continue such a dialogue
so as to enhance understanding and reduce differences.

Spring told Qian that the EU supports China's entry into the World
Trade Organization, hoping the question can be solved on an equal and
just base.

On the human rights issue, Qian reaffirmed China's consistent policy
that is to carry out dialogues with other countries on the basis of
equality and mutual respect.

China believes that dialogues and confrontation cannot be mixed
together. If any country wishes to seek dialogues with China, it should
discard the stance of confrontation, he added.

On behalf of the European Union, Hans Van Mierlo expressed his
gratitude for the flexibility and constructive spirit China had
demonstrated in the negotiations for settling the Comprehensive Test
Ban Treaty (CTBT). He said China had made important contribution to the
successful adoption of the treaty earlier this months.

The Chinese vice-premier said that China had been actively involved in
the CTBT negotiations, holding that it would be the first step taken
toward the final target of a comprehensive ban and complete destruction
of nuclear weapons. He said the international community should continue
its efforts in this regard.

Copyright 1996 China Business Information Network




