CHINA BUSINESS INFORMATION NETWORK via NewsNet
September 25, 1996

Beijing plans expansion of overseas labor service

from CHINA BUSINESS INFORMATION NETWORK (CBnet), Sep. 25, 1996

Beijing plans to send thousands of experts and skilled people to other
countries as part of a 15-year plan to boost its share of overseas
contracts.

The city has announced an expansion of its overseas labor services and
construction co-operation, with an increase of 10 to 15 per cent
annually, a top municipal official said.

He said by the year 2000, the total turnover of overseas labor services
is expected to reach up to $600 million US dollars, and by $1.4 billion
US dollars by the year 2010.

A number of effective measures are to be taken to achieve the goal,
said Yi Xiqun, director of the Beijing Municipal Foreign Trade
Commission. The most important is to extend overseas contracts and
labor services in accordance with international standards.

By the end of 1995, Beijing had signed contracts for overseas projects
and labor services totalling $2.57 billion US dollar, with a turnover
of $1.13 billion US dollars.

More than 20,000 doctors, scientists and engineers have been sent to
over 50 countries and regions around the world, the official said.

A total 11 enterprises in the city have now been licensed to enjoy the
right to sign overseas contracts for labor services.

Among them, the Beijing Urban and Rural Construction Group Corp is the
biggest, he said.

Last year, the city signed contracts for overseas cooperative projects
and labor services worth $780 million US dollars, earning millions of
dollars in profits for China.

